-- Bank of China, China Overseas Land, PetroChina: Hong Kong Equities Preview
-- Hanny Wan
-- 2010-04-28T01:08:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-04-28/bank-of-china-china-overseas-land-petrochina-hong-kong-equities-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  
 The Hang Seng Index slid 1.5 percent to 21,261.79. The Hang
Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, declined 1.7 percent to 12,171.01.  
 Developers: China’s recent efforts to cool its property
market are “just the beginning,” the China Daily newspaper
said in an editorial today.  
 Beijing will issue policies today limiting how many homes
residents of the Chinese capital are allowed to buy, the
Shanghai Securities News reported, citing an unidentified person.  
 A halt on share sales by Chinese developers may affect 45
companies with plans to raise as much as 110 billion yuan ($16
billion), the China Daily reported, citing an unidentified
source close to the China Securities Regulatory Commission.  
 China Overseas Land & Investment Ltd. (688 HK), controlled
by the nation’s construction ministry, declined 0.7 percent to
HK$14.70. China Resources Land Ltd. (1109 HK), a state-
controlled developer, fell 2.8 percent to HK$14.06.  
 Bank of China Ltd. (3988 HK): The nation’s third-largest
lender by market value said first-quarter profit rose 41 percent
to 26.23 billion yuan, aided by rising demand for loans and fee-
based services. Profit beat the 25 billion yuan average estimate
of six analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. The stock slid 1 percent
to HK$4.04.  
 PetroChina Co. (857 HK): Asia’s biggest company by market
value posted a 71 percent jump in first-quarter profit to 32.5
billion yuan as demand surged and oil prices rebounded. That
beat the median estimate of 30.9 billion yuan in a Bloomberg
survey of six analysts. The stock fell 1.4 percent to HK$9.10.  
 Wheelock & Co. (20 HK): The Hong Kong-based company that
through a unit controls two of the city’s biggest shopping malls,
offered to pay HK$6.9 billion ($889 million) to buy Wheelock
Properties Ltd. (49 HK) shares it doesn’t already own. Wheelock
agreed to pay HK$13 in cash for each share in the unit, a 144
percent premium above its closing price on April 16, the last
day the stock traded, the company said. Wheelock retreated 1.9
percent to HK$23.35.  
 ZTE Corp. (763 HK): China’s second-biggest maker of phone
equipment said first-quarter net income rose 40 percent to 109.9
million yuan. The stock dropped 1.6 percent to HK$46.65.  
